# Bioluminescent Marine Snow Walkthrough

## What Was Completed
 - Successfully added mouse interaction to the scene by setting up a `window.addEventListener("mousedown")` in [index.js](file:///Users/2b/Library/CloudStorage/GoogleDrive-brian.rio11@gmail.com/My%20Drive/%F0%9F%94%B5/01%20Grad%20School/02%20SP26/03%20It%27s%20Shader%20Time/W8%20-%20GPU%20Computing/src/index.js).
 - Updated the `RawShaderMaterial` (`pointsMat`) to accept the `uLastClickTime` metric from JavaScript.
 - Enabled `THREE.AdditiveBlending` on the points to give overlapping particles a naturally glowing, light-emitting, bioluminescent look. 
 - Altered [render.vert](file:///Users/2b/Library/CloudStorage/GoogleDrive-brian.rio11@gmail.com/My%20Drive/%F0%9F%94%B5/01%20Grad%20School/02%20SP26/03%20It%27s%20Shader%20Time/W8%20-%20GPU%20Computing/src/shaders/render.vert) to properly pass down Particle UV coordinates.
 - Completely overhauled [render.frag](file:///Users/2b/Library/CloudStorage/GoogleDrive-brian.rio11@gmail.com/My%20Drive/%F0%9F%94%B5/01%20Grad%20School/02%20SP26/03%20It%27s%20Shader%20Time/W8%20-%20GPU%20Computing/src/shaders/render.frag) to do the following math during rendering:
    1. Check exactly how much time has passed since the user clicked (`max(0.0, uTime - uLastClickTime)`).
    2. Add a `vUv` random offset so every particle blinks independently instead of synchronized.
    3. Calculate a non-linear sine wave that gets visibly slower over time (`sin(15.0 * pow(timeSinceClick, 0.8))`).
    4. Implement an Exponential Decay Multiplier (`exp(-timeSinceClick * 0.4)`) to make particles fade over time.
    5. Output the result multiplied by a bright neon blue vector to the screen!

## How to Test
1. Make sure your local browser tab at `http://localhost:8000` is open.
2. Refresh the page so the browser downloads the latest [.frag](file:///Users/2b/Library/CloudStorage/GoogleDrive-brian.rio11@gmail.com/My%20Drive/%F0%9F%94%B5/01%20Grad%20School/02%20SP26/03%20It%27s%20Shader%20Time/W3%20-%20Shader%20Pipeline/map.frag) changes.
3. The screen will start completely black (or mostly black, if you only just opened it). 
4. Click your mouse button anywhere on the canvas.
5. Watch the marine snow light up rapidly in neon blue, flicker violently, slow down its flickering tempo gracefully, and then decay safely back down to pure pitch black.
